The tradition of Montenegro’s engagement with international affairs dates back to the Byzantine era, when it was an ally of Constantinople and maintained a close political and economic relationship. Apart from its fortress and naval capabilities, Montenegro elevated diplomatic relations with the representatives of other states within its territory. In 1791, the Metropolitan of the Episcopal See, bishop of Ulcinj, Bishop Teodosije, suggested opening the first diplomatic representation in Austria (which would have consequences in the future with the Austrians later occupying Montenegro for 44 years), with the Miratovic brothers representing Montenegro in Vienna. Around the same period, the Nykirchen brothers, Steve and Mikic, worked as representatives of Montenegro in Austria-Hungary, Roman Empire, Bulgaria, Romania, Turkey and Greece. Their work is known to have contributed to recognition of Montenegrin statehood on the European scene, especially in the circles of the Imperial Court of Budapest and Vienna and the Eastern Orthodox Church.
